==English==
===Etymology===
From modern Latin [[Batrachia]], former name of the zoological order ''Anura'', from Greek [[βατραχεια]], neuter plural of adjective from [[βατραχος]] ‘frog’.

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /bə'tɹeɪkɪən/

===Noun===
'''batrachian'''
# a [[frog]] or [[toad]]

===Adjective===
'''batrachian'''
# pertaining to a [[frog]] or [[toad]]
#:*'''1939''': At this Lena smiled again with that mirthless '''batrachian''' grin.  (Miller, ''Tropic Of Capricorn'')
#:*'''1965''': His '''batrachian''' lips pursed into a smile, and he dug again into the honey.  (Fowles, ''The Magus'')

===Synonyms===
*[[anuran]]